<paragraph id="8BA443409FCFA4C5E6A7FC07FD71ACF0" blockId="227.[140,1108,976,1636]" box="[140,695,976,1003]" pageId="227" pageNumber="228">
<heading id="D0ECF42C9FCFA4C5E6A7FC07FD71ACF0" box="[140,695,976,1003]" fontSize="11" level="2" pageId="227" pageNumber="228" reason="3">
<emphasis id="B96F9F529FCFA4C5E6A7FC07FD71ACF0" bold="true" box="[140,695,976,1003]" italics="true" pageId="227" pageNumber="228">
58. 
<taxonomicName id="4C1B38C39FCFA4C5E693FC07FE83ACF0" box="[184,325,976,1003]" class="Insecta" family="Sphingidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="227" pageNumber="228" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Sphingidae</taxonomicName>
– sphinx moths; hawk moths
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C30110CB9FCFA4C5E6A7FC24FCC4A97F" pageId="227" pageNumber="228" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BA443409FCFA4C5E6A7FC24FE05ABFA" blockId="227.[140,1108,976,1636]" pageId="227" pageNumber="228">
Medium-sized to very large (
<quantity id="4CE3EEA59FCFA4C5E7E7FC23FD9CAB15" box="[460,602,1012,1038]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.05" metricValueMax="1.8" metricValueMin="0.3" pageId="227" pageNumber="228" unit="mm" value="105.0" valueMax="180.0" valueMin="30.0">30–180 mm</quantity>
wingspan) moths with robust bodies, a characteristic elongate–triangular forewing, and a relatively small hindwing. Like the 
<taxonomicName id="4C1B38C39FCFA4C5E20CFBC0FF2BAB4F" class="Insecta" family="Saturniidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="227" pageNumber="228" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Saturniidae</taxonomicName>
, the sphinx moths are part of the “charismatic megafauna” of 
<taxonomicName id="4C1B38C39FCFA4C5E5B1FBEDFBE5AB4F" box="[922,1059,1082,1108]" class="Insecta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="227" pageNumber="228" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="order">Lepidoptera</taxonomicName>
and indeed of all insects. Larvae often attract attention because they are large, and most species bear a conspicuous horn on the dorsal tip of the abdomen. Larval host plants include a wide variety of plant groups, although many of the species listed here feed on deciduous trees and shrubs.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BA443409FCFA4C5E692FB3DFC36AA76" blockId="227.[140,1108,976,1636]" pageId="227" pageNumber="228">
There are at least 1 200 species of sphingids globally, and the family is most diverse in tropical regions (Lemaire and Minet 1999). Th e North American fauna consists of about 130 species, with 27 species reported from AB. Many sphingids are strong dispersers, and strays from the far south occur occasionally in southern 
<collectingCountry id="F30C03D09FCFA4C5E5BAFA84FC2DAA76" box="[913,1003,1363,1389]" name="Canada" pageId="227" pageNumber="228">Canada</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BA443409FCFA4C5E692FAA0FCC4A97F" blockId="227.[140,1108,976,1636]" pageId="227" pageNumber="228">
Three important monographs cover the North American 
<taxonomicName id="4C1B38C39FCFA4C5E560FAA0FC0BAA8A" box="[843,973,1399,1425]" class="Insecta" family="Sphingidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="227" pageNumber="228" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Sphingidae</taxonomicName>
: 
<bibRefCitation id="EF8A3EB19FCFA4C5E5F3FAA0FE98AAAF" author="Rothschild LW &amp; Jordan K" pageId="227" pageNumber="228" pagination="1 - 972" refId="ref264960" refString="Rothschild LW, Jordan K (1903) A revision of the lepidopterous family Sphinigdae. Novitates Zoologicae 9 (suppl.): 1 - 972." type="journal article" year="1903">
Rothschild and 
<collectingCountry id="F30C03D09FCFA4C5E697FA4DFEC1AAAF" box="[188,263,1434,1460]" name="Jordan" pageId="227" pageNumber="228">Jordan</collectingCountry>
(1903)
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="EF8A3EB19FCFA4C5E742FA4DFDD0AAAF" author="Hodges RW" box="[361,534,1434,1460]" pageId="227" pageNumber="228" refId="ref249071" refString="Hodges RW (1971) Sphingoidea; hawkmoths. Fasc. 21. In: Dominick RB, Ferguson DC, Franclemont JG, Hodges RW, Munroe EG (Eds) Th e moths of America north of Mexico. Wedge Entomological Research Foundation, Washington, D. C., 158 pp. + 14 plates." type="book" year="1971">Hodges (1971)</bibRefCitation>
, and 
<bibRefCitation id="EF8A3EB19FCFA4C5E47AFA4DFD2AAAAF" author="Tuttle JP" box="[593,748,1434,1460]" pageId="227" pageNumber="228" refId="ref268908" refString="Tuttle JP (2007) Th e hawk moths of North America. Wedge Entomological Research Foundation, Washington D. C., xvii + 253 pp." type="book" year="2007">Tuttle (2007)</bibRefCitation>
. 
<bibRefCitation id="EF8A3EB19FCFA4C5E4DDFA4DFB95AAAF" author="Rothschild LW &amp; Jordan K" box="[758,1107,1434,1460]" pageId="227" pageNumber="228" pagination="1 - 972" refId="ref264960" refString="Rothschild LW, Jordan K (1903) A revision of the lepidopterous family Sphinigdae. Novitates Zoologicae 9 (suppl.): 1 - 972." type="journal article" year="1903">Rothschild and Jordan’s (1903)</bibRefCitation>
monumental work encompassed a global revision of the family. 
<bibRefCitation id="EF8A3EB19FCFA4C5E546FA6AFBDCAACC" author="Hodges RW" box="[877,1050,1469,1495]" pageId="227" pageNumber="228" refId="ref249071" refString="Hodges RW (1971) Sphingoidea; hawkmoths. Fasc. 21. In: Dominick RB, Ferguson DC, Franclemont JG, Hodges RW, Munroe EG (Eds) Th e moths of America north of Mexico. Wedge Entomological Research Foundation, Washington, D. C., 158 pp. + 14 plates." type="book" year="1971">Hodges (1971)</bibRefCitation>
provided a taxonomic framework and biological information, although the distributions in western 
<collectingCountry id="F30C03D09FCFA4C5E721F9D4FEA6A906" box="[266,352,1539,1565]" name="Canada" pageId="227" pageNumber="228">Canada</collectingCountry>
were sketchy. 
<bibRefCitation id="EF8A3EB19FCFA4C5E42DF9D4FD66A905" author="Tuttle JP" box="[518,672,1539,1566]" pageId="227" pageNumber="228" refId="ref268908" refString="Tuttle JP (2007) Th e hawk moths of North America. Wedge Entomological Research Foundation, Washington D. C., xvii + 253 pp." type="book" year="2007">Tuttle (2007)</bibRefCitation>
provided a wealth of biological information with much better coverage of western 
<collectingCountry id="F30C03D09FCFA4C5E48AF9F0FD3DA95A" box="[673,763,1575,1601]" name="Canada" pageId="227" pageNumber="228">Canada</collectingCountry>
. 
<bibRefCitation id="EF8A3EB19FCFA4C5E523F9F0FB95A95A" author="Kitching IJ &amp; Cadiou J-M" box="[776,1107,1575,1601]" pageId="227" pageNumber="228" refId="ref251267" refString="Kitching IJ, Cadiou J-M (2000) Hawkmoths of the world: an annotated and illustrated revisionary checklist (Lepidoptera: Sphingidae). Cornell University Press, Ithaca, NY and The Natural History Museum, London, UK, 226 pp." type="book" year="2000">Kitching and Cadiou (2000)</bibRefCitation>
provided a complete catalogue of the world 
<taxonomicName id="4C1B38C39FCFA4C5E457F99DFD38A97F" box="[636,766,1610,1636]" class="Insecta" family="Sphingidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="227" pageNumber="228" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Sphingidae</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
